The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business
 Thursday, February 05, 2004  Business Briefs																								 Mumbai, Feb. 4: The Reserve Bank of India (RBI) has allowed multilateral development banks, which are specifically permitted by the Centre to float rupee bonds in India, to purchase government securities (g-secs). With this permission, institutions such as International Finance Corporation and Asian Development Bank can buy g-secs in the Indian market. 																								 Mumbai, Feb. 4: The RBI has formulated a remittance scheme, allowing resident individuals to remit up to $25,000 per calendar year for current or capital account transaction or a combination of both. The scheme will come into operation with immediate effect.																								 Mumbai, Feb. 4: Patni Computers Systems initial public offering (IPO) was oversubscribed by 8.96 times till today, the penultimate day of the 100 per cent book built issue, with maximum bids at Rs 230 per share.																								 Mumbai, Feb. 4: D-Link Corp of Taiwan is raising its stake in D-Link (India) to 40 per cent from the existing 34.51 per cent following an approval from the Foreign Investment Promotion Board.																								 Ahmedabad, Feb. 4: Dishman Pharmaceuticals and Chemicals Ltd will enter the capital market in the first week of March with its proposed IPO of 3,433,500 shares of Rs 10 each. The issue would constitute 25 per cent of the fully diluted post-issue paid-up capital of the company and the IPO would be through 100 per cent book building route, managing director J. R. Vyas said. 																								 Mumbai, Feb. 4: Indian Hotels Company (IHCL), a Tata group company, has raised $150 million through foreign currency convertible bonds issue, which was oversubscribed by more than 20 times, to fund acquisitions, expansion and modernisation at home and abroad.																								 New Delhi, Feb. 4: The government has asked the Telecom Regulatory Authority of India (Trai) for inputs on revenue sharing and spectrum management for FM radio even as it is considering the Amit Mitra task force report on the second round of licensing in this sector.
